/*************************************************** JAVA ***********************************************/

Optimal Solution - We compute subtree heights bottom-up and immediately return -1 whenever a node is unbalanced to avoid unnecessary traversal.


class Solution {
    // Returns true if the binary tree is height-balanced
    public boolean isBalanced(TreeNode root) {
        // If dfsHeight returns -1, tree is unbalanced
        return dfsHeight(root) != -1;
    }
    // Helper function to compute height
    // Returns -1 if subtree is unbalanced
    private int dfsHeight(TreeNode root) {
        // Base case: empty subtree has height 0
        if (root == null)
            return 0;
        // Compute left subtree height
        int leftHeight = dfsHeight(root.left);
        if (leftHeight == -1)
            return -1; // Left subtree already unbalanced
        // Compute right subtree height
        int rightHeight = dfsHeight(root.right);
        if (rightHeight == -1)
            return -1; // Right subtree already unbalanced
        // If current node is unbalanced
        if (Math.abs(leftHeight - rightHeight) > 1)
            return -1;
        // Return height of current subtree
        return Math.max(leftHeight, rightHeight) + 1;
    }
}

Time Complexity :- O(N).
Space Complexity :- O(H). height of the tree.
